    <text>
        <body>
            <head>83. Memorandum From the Deputy Secretary of State (<persName
                    corresp="recrWcRZxYT57GiP4">Dam</persName>) to Secretary of State <persName
                    corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d83fn1">Source: Department of State,
                    Bureau of <rs corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">Arms Control and
                        Disarmament</rs>, Lot 01D127, 1969–1990 Subject Records of <persName
                        corresp="recoqpx2aNuHTDUHK">James P. Timbie</persName>, Box 2, Papers for
                    DepSec <persName corresp="recrWcRZxYT57GiP4">Ken Dam</persName>, 1983–1985.
                    Secret. A stamped notation indicates <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN"
                        >Shultz</persName> saw the memorandum.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1983-10-11"
                        >October 11, 1983</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>Framework for <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss>
                </item>
            </list>
            <p>You have discussed with the <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq"
                    >President</persName> the concept of tradeoffs which take into account
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName> advantages in <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs> and <placeName
                    corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName> advantages in large missiles.
                    <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">The President</persName> has now publicly
                endorsed this idea, and included it in the recent <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> NSDD.<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d83fn2">See <ref target="#d82"
                        >Document 82</ref>.</note>
            </p>
            <p>Now we need to follow up with a way to implement this approach that is simple,
                practical, and builds on our present proposal. The approach<note n="3" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d83fn3">Not further identified.</note> suggested by General <persName
                    corresp="rec8U08PO6l3eKNwV">Kent</persName> is too complex to be the basis for
                an agreement.</p>
            <pb facs="0324" n="295" xml:id="pg_295"/>
            <p>The attached paper outlines a logical way to proceed. It implements the guidance in
                the recent <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> NSDD, and does so in a way that emphasizes simplicity. Additional features
                could be added, for example, to further discourage land-based <gloss
                    target="#t_MIRV_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">MIRV</rs>
                </gloss> missiles, at a cost of additional complexity.</p>
            <p>
                <persName corresp="recUlzLYy5aEOn1C0">Larry Eagleburger</persName> has reviewed this
                approach and believes it makes sense. We would like a meeting with you to discuss
                these ideas.<note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d83fn4">
                    <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName> drew a downward–facing
                    arrow in the right-hand margin beside the first paragraph of the memorandum
                    pointing down to this paragraph, drew two short vertical lines to the right of
                    this paragraph, and wrote: “<hi rendition="simple_italic">Yes</hi> G.”</note>
            </p>
            <p>I am also giving copies to <persName corresp="recWfOZtO0phY5iDk">Jon Howe</persName>
                and <persName corresp="reccOrOPn6TsvnrGI">Rick Burt</persName> for their
                comments.</p>
            <frus:attachment xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0">
                <note>
                    <hi rendition="simple_bold">Attachment</hi>
                </note>
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="simple_bold">Paper Prepared in the Department of State</hi>
                    <note n="5" place="foot" xml:id="d83fn5">Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian">undated</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rendition="simple_centre">
                    <hi rendition="simple_italic">FRAMEWORK FOR <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                            <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                        </gloss>
                    </hi>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">The President</persName> has recently
                    decided that the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United
                        States</placeName> is prepared to:</p>
                <quote>
                    <p>—make tradeoffs that take into account <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL"
                            >U.S.</placeName> advantages and interests and <placeName
                            corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName> advantages and interests,
                        providing each side maximum flexibility consistent with movement toward a
                        more stable balance of forces;</p>
                    <p>—explore ways to further limit the size and capability of <gloss
                            target="#t_ALCM_1">
                            <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCM</rs>
                        </gloss> forces; and</p>
                    <p>—address the destructive capacity of <rs type="topic"
                            corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs> as well as <rs type="topic"
                            corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">missiles</rs>.</p>
                </quote>
                <p>This memorandum outlines a framework for a <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss> agreement that implements these concepts. It would require substantial
                        <rs type="topic" corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k">reductions</rs> to equal levels
                    of forces, and discourage destabilizing systems such as large, <gloss
                        target="#t_MIRV_1">
                        <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">MIRVed</rs>
                    </gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                        <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                    </gloss>. It is based on the current <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL"
                        >U.S.</placeName> proposal, but also adopts features of the <placeName
                        corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName> proposal.</p>
                <p>Consideration of equitable tradeoffs between missile and bomber forces is
                    complicated by substantial differences in speed, in the defenses they face, and
                    in their potential for a <rs corresp="recvZDidU8pZ1fdw1" type="topic">first
                        strike</rs>. The challenge is to find a formula that allows considerable
                    flexibility in structuring forces, but recognizes these differences and
                    discourages destabilizing systems such as large, <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1">
                        <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">MIRVed</rs>
                    </gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                        <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                    </gloss>.</p>
                <pb facs="0325" n="296" xml:id="pg_296"/>
                <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Elements of a <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss> Agreement</p>
                <quote>
                    <p>—Limit on the total number of missile <rs type="topic"
                            corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> plus <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                            <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                        </gloss>.</p>
                    <p>—<rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">Sublimit</rs> on missile <rs
                            type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> (e.g.,
                        5,000).</p>
                    <p>—Constrain destructive capability by limits on the number of heavy and medium
                        missiles and <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs>.</p>
                    <p>—Limit on the total number of strategic missiles and <rs type="topic"
                            corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs> (e.g., 1800).</p>
                </quote>
                <p>The <hi rendition="simple_italic">combined limit on missile <gloss
                            target="#t_RV_1">RVs</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                            <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                        </gloss>
                    </hi> excludes other bomber weapons (short-range missiles and bombs) as part of
                    the compensation for <rs type="topic" corresp="recY4zdE5fZQUvoyu"
                        >air-defenses</rs> and other factors. To ensure that <gloss
                        target="#t_ALCM_1">
                        <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                    </gloss> are treated in a different manner than missile <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>, there would be a <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs> on missile <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>, and <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                        <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                    </gloss> would be counted on a two-for-one basis. Such a constraint on <gloss
                        target="#t_ALCM_1">
                        <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCM</rs>
                    </gloss> numbers would permit our planned <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                        <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCM</rs>
                    </gloss>
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recXAkrxnavJi6JiT">deployments</rs>, and would be
                    consistent with <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the President</persName>’s
                    decision to explore ways to further limit the size and capability of <gloss
                        target="#t_ALCM_1">
                        <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCM</rs>
                    </gloss> forces.</p>
                <p>The <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                        <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs> on missile <rs
                            type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>
                    </hi> recognizes the differences between missile <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> and <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                        <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                    </gloss>, and would prevent <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3"
                        >Soviet</placeName> allocation of all of their total to missile <rs
                        type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>. Additional <rs
                        corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs> could be added (e.g.
                    on <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1">
                        <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">MIRVed</rs>
                    </gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                        <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                    </gloss>
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>) to further constrain
                    destabilizing systems, at a cost of increased complexity.</p>
                <p>Since equality in warhead numbers does not result in equality in <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recAynYh8uzxYGQRH">strategic forces</rs> if there are gross
                    disparities in warhead size, there must also be constraints on <hi
                        rendition="simple_italic">destructive capability</hi>. In addition,
                        <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the President</persName> has directed
                    that we consider constraints that address the destructive capacity of <rs
                        type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs>. One way to accomplish
                    these objectives would be to expand our collateral constraints on large missiles
                    to include <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs> as well.
                    The 110/210 limits in our current position could be raised (e.g., to 150 heavy
                        <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                        <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                    </gloss> and 400 heavy and medium <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                        <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                    </gloss>), and a third category added that included <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs> (e.g., 550 heavy and medium <gloss
                        target="#t_ICBM_1">
                        <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                    </gloss> and <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs>).
                    Inclusion of <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs> would
                    recognize the destructive capability of <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs>, and give some flexibility to
                    choose between large missiles and <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE"
                        >bombers</rs>. The <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName>
                    could have a large bomber force and 100 or more <gloss target="#t_MX_2">
                        <rs corresp="rec99k2btquR4fVXS" type="topic">M–X</rs>
                    </gloss> missiles; the Soviets could have 400 <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recGXoMuZAGqhZK03">SS–17</rs>/<rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recAug8nb5QfVfzky">18</rs>/<rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recdBW6E9ogkYvqAR">19</rs>/<rs type="topic"
                        corresp="rec3W7wxuFTsr0A52">24</rs>
                    <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                        <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                    </gloss> (about half their current total) and a smaller bomber force. In order
                    to place meaningful constraints on destructive capability, such indirect limits
                    need to be supplemented with <rs type="topic" corresp="recbm2CDfl6YlSCnq"
                        >modernization</rs> constraints such as the limits in our present position
                    on the warhead weight of new missiles.</p>
                <p>The limits on destructive capability will be controversial both within the
                        <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName> Government and with
                    the Soviets. Other alternatives for accomplishing this objective can be
                    explored, such as limits on warhead weight, as well as complex formulas for
                    measuring the destructive capacity of missiles and <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs>.</p>
                <pb facs="0326" n="297" xml:id="pg_297"/>
                <p>Finally, while <hi rendition="simple_italic">limits on the number of missiles and
                            <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs>
                    </hi> would add little to the constraints on <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> and destructive capability, and
                    the <orgName corresp="recilTL8Sxklv18up">Scowcroft Commission</orgName>
                    recommended against low limits, both sides have proposed such limits. The
                        <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName> proposal for a
                    total of 1,800 missiles and <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE"
                        >bombers</rs> is consistent with the approach outlined here, and <placeName
                        corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName> acceptance could be a
                    quid-pro-quo for <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName>
                    acceptance of other elements of our proposal.</p>
                <p>The approach suggested here would give both sides freedom to choose—within
                    limits—the mix of missile and bomber forces, with additional constraints on
                    destabilizing systems. There is no magic formula. Definition of equitable
                    tradeoffs between missiles and <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE"
                        >bombers</rs> is somewhat arbitrary, and agreement on such tradeoffs will be
                    difficult to achieve both within the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL"
                        >U.S.</placeName> and with the Soviets. As <persName
                        corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the President</persName> has directed, this is a
                    necessary step toward the achievement of significant reductions. There is no
                    prospect that either side will agree to mirror image the other’s forces.</p>
            </frus:attachment>
